            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Darius Khoury\u2019s life is steeped in the aromas of two worlds: the za'atar and fresh-baked man'oushe of his parents' Daly City bakery, and the damp, eucalyptus-scented fog of the Bay Area. A second-generation Lebanese-American, he grew up bridging the gap between his parents' stories of a vibrant, pre-war Beirut and the suburban rhythm of his American childhood. These dual narratives ignited his passion for storytelling, not as escapism, but as a way of understanding the world.\n\nHe pursued a Communications degree at San Francisco State University, drawn to the city's eclectic energy. His early career was a grind in public radio, learning the craft of audio production through long hours and low pay. The 2008 recession was a defining crucible; laid off from his junior producer role, he was forced to freelance. This difficult period, however, pushed him toward the burgeoning world of podcasting, where he found a more dynamic and innovative home for his skills. He adeptly navigated the industry's evolution, rising from a contract sound editor to a Senior Producer at a prominent informational podcast network in SoMa.\n\nNow 41, Darius\u2019s life has found a comfortable, if busy, rhythm. His 3.5-mile MUNI commute from his Mission District apartment to his downtown office is a daily ritual, a time to decompress while listening to the very media he helps create. He shares his apartment with his partner of eight years, Ben, a landscape architect. Their social life revolves around a tight-knit circle of friends, often hosting dinner parties that blend Middle Eastern flavors with California sensibilities.\n\nDarius has a complicated love for San Francisco. He cherishes the city\u2019s progressive ideals and the ability to walk to a dozen world-class cafes and bookstores, yet he worries that the affordability crisis is eroding the creative soul that first drew him here. His dream is to leverage his position to launch his own flagship podcast\u2014a docuseries on the modern diaspora, tracing stories of identity and belonging that mirror his own. Personally, he and Ben aspire to buy a small condo in the city, a tangible anchor in the place that has shaped every facet of his adult life."
        },
