            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being seven, standing on a milk crate in the Daly City bakery. The air was thick with the scent of yeast and warm za'atar. He watched his father\u2019s strong hands stretch the dough for man'oushe, flour dusting his forearms like a second skin. It wasn't just baking; it was a ritual, a silent story of a place called Beirut he\u2019d only ever heard about. That feeling of heritage, transmitted through warmth and scent, planted the seed of his desire to capture stories that live beyond words. This happened around 1989.\n\n2.\nThe layoff email in 2008 arrived with a cold, digital finality. He sat in his tiny SF State-era apartment, the radio he loved now silent, feeling the city's promise evaporate. The panic was a physical weight in his chest. For a week, he felt like a ghost haunting his own life. But that fear became a fire. It forced him off the established path and into the uncertain world of freelancing, where he discovered podcasting. That moment of failure inadvertently gave him his entire career. He was 26.\n\n3.\nIt was their third date, a walk through the Presidio on a rare, sun-drenched January afternoon. Ben, a landscape architect, was explaining how the cypress trees were shaped by the wind, his voice full of passion. Darius stopped listening to the words and just heard the sound\u2014the steady, calm cadence of it. In that moment, surrounded by the scent of eucalyptus and sea salt, he felt a profound sense of peace. He knew, with startling clarity, that this was home. This was just over eight years ago, when he was 33.\n\n4.\nHe remembers an interview he produced two years ago with an elderly woman who had fled Iran in '79. After an hour, she forgot the microphone, her voice softening as she described the garden she left behind. In the silence between her words, Darius heard the echo of his own parents\u2019 stories. It was the first time his work felt truly sacred\u2014not just editing audio, but curating a soul. That interview became the catalyst for his dream of a docuseries, a mission to preserve those delicate, fading histories.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on his MUNI commute home, the J-Church lurched to a stop with a view of Dolores Park. He saw picnickers sprawled on the grass, a glittering tech shuttle gliding past, and a man pushing a cart of scavenged cans. The whole beautiful, fractured soul of the city was in that single frame. A wave of fierce love and deep anxiety washed over him. This city had forged him, and the desperate wish to buy a small piece of it\u2014to truly belong\u2014felt more urgent than ever."
